<div id="review_3104333722" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3104333722" />
    <a title="ValeReads Kyriosity" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3123581-valereads-kyriosity"><img alt="ValeReads Kyriosity" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1423552725p2/3123581.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3104333722?book_show_action=true">Dec 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="ValeReads Kyriosity" class="user" itemprop="url" name="ValeReads Kyriosity" href="/user/show/3123581-valereads-kyriosity">ValeReads Kyriosity</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook 9780786117963" href="/book/show/7440215-surprised-by-joy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3123581-valereads-kyriosity?shelf=audiobooks">audiobooks</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3123581-valereads-kyriosity?shelf=biography-memoir">biography-memoir</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3104333722" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10811894543569103016">I read this in high school (discovered a four-leaf clover pressed in it that probably dates from then), but I can&apos;t recall if I&apos;ve ever reread it. I know I couldn&apos;t possibly have understood much of it then, and even though I followed relatively more closely now, Lewis&apos;s philosophizing and literary copiousness leave me in the dust. Heck, the size of Lewis&apos;s brain would leave Jeeves&apos;s in the dust. And yet, once he got past his adolescent priggishness (there once was a boy called Clive Staples Lewi</span>
  <span id="freeText10811894543569103016" style="display:none">I read this in high school (discovered a four-leaf clover pressed in it that probably dates from then), but I can't recall if I've ever reread it. I know I couldn't possibly have understood much of it then, and even though I followed relatively more closely now, Lewis's philosophizing and literary copiousness leave me in the dust. Heck, the size of Lewis's brain would leave Jeeves's in the dust. And yet, once he got past his adolescent priggishness (there once was a boy called Clive Staples Lewis, and he almost deserved it [ooh, look...I can do literary allusions, too!]), his humility, too, leaves me in the dust. Lewis is always reliable in his understanding of human nature, but maintaining such a keen eye when looking in a mirror is an especially rare skill.<br /><br />Once again, I was too busy about the house to interrupt my listening much for noting and sharing commonplaces, but I managed to grab this one: “When the boy passes from nursery literature to school stories he is going down, not up. Peter Rabbit pleases a disinterested imagination, for the child does not want to be a rabbit, though he may like pretending to be a rabbit as he may later like acting as Hamlet; but the story of the unpromising boy who became captain of the First Eleven exists precisely to feed his real ambitions.” <br /><br />I think this tells us what Jack would have thought of Harry Potter, which is very much of the British school story genre. Not to mention vast swaths of self-indulgent American middle grade/y.a. literature. OK, OK, so HP isn't the <i>very</i> schooliest of school stories, but I do think it fits the bill in the basics. And what's more, the school stories of Jack's youth couldn't possibly have included neeeeearly as much whiiiiiining!<br /><br />Once again, Ralph Cosham (Geoffrey Howard) is a sturdy narrator. So sturdy is he in my experience that I was quite startled when he stuck an extra syllable into <i>quiddity</i>, which he pronounced <i>quiddidity</i>. Twice. It reminded me of the fourth syllable Bekah Merkle always shoehorns into <i>Wollstonecraft</i>. I of course forgive them both with much affection, especially since I've many much more of such mistakes to be forgiven from myself. 😉</span>
  <a data-text-id="10811894543569103016" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


